{{Short description|Israeli-American painter}}{{Multiple issues|{{More citations needed|date=June 2016}}{{Notability|date=October 2018}}}} {{Infobox artist | name = Guy Ben-Ari | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1984}} | birth_place = [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]] | nationality = | field = [[Painting]], [[Drawing]], [[Printmaking]] | training = [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]], [[Columbia University]] [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]], [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] }}
'''Guy Ben-Ari''' (born 1984 in [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]]) is an Israeli painter living and working in [[New York City]].
== Biography == Ben-Ari received his [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] from [[Columbia University]]'s School of the Arts in 2011, and his [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]] with honors from [[Bezalel Academy of Art and Design]] in [[Jerusalem]] in 2009, where he received the Presser Award for Excellence in Painting.{{Citation needed|date = April 2016}} In 2008, Ben-Ari was selected for the Exchange Program for Merit Students to study Painting at the [[Slade School of Fine Art]], [[University College London|UCL]], [[London]].{{Citation needed|date = April 2016}}
Ben-Ari's body of work focuses on the connection between [[Psychoanalytic theory]], [[Semiotics]] and the medium of painting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://voxpopuligallery.org/exhibitions/yes-to-burning-eyes/|title=Yes to Burning Eyes|last=|first=|date=2012|website=voxpopuligallery.org|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref> Following the Psychoanalyst [[Jacques Lacan]]’s notion that 'The word kills the thing'<ref>Lacan, Jacques (1977). Ecrits. A Selection. Trans. A. Sheridan. London, Tavistock. p. 319</ref> by fixing its meaning, he uses an illustrative approach to examine the way metaphors, when taken literally, become dysfunctional. Ben-Ari is interested in the implications of using painting, a medium that rejects [[literal interpretation]], to analyze concepts that reject visual interpretation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lmcc.net/person/guy-ben-ari/|title=Guy Ben-Ari|website=Lower Manhattan Cultural Council|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-19}}</ref> Ben-Ari's recent work uses painting as a framework to study elements of [[post-structuralism]] and psychoanalytic theory. Much of his work originates in [[jokes]] or [[illustration]]s of related concepts and situations, as he attempts to employ a literal strategy in an image, without collapsing into a mere illustration.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Artis Agenda|title=Guy Ben-Ari: Yes to Burning Eyes at Vox Populi Gallery, Philadelphia |url=http://www.artiscontemporary.org/agenda_detail.php?id=577|year=2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aicf.org/event/guy-ben-ari-2/|title=Guy Ben-Ari, Out of Sight – Solo Exhibition|last=|first=|date=2013|work=America-Israel Cultural Foundation|access-date=2018-10-03|language=en-US}}</ref>
Since 2009, Ben-Ari runs an arts cultural group with artist [[Leah Wolf]] called ''Meta Meta Meta'', to help support the arts in their community in Brooklyn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://patch.com/new-york/heights-dumbo/brooklyn-management-company-offers-dozen-artists-low-rent-dumbo-studios|title=Brooklyn Management Company Offers A Dozen Artists Low-Rent DUMBO Studios|date=2017-03-21|work=Brooklyn Heights-DUMBO, NY Patch|access-date=2018-10-03|language=en-US}}</ref>
Ben-Ari is a recent artist-in-residence at the Lower East Side Printshop, Triangle Arts in Brooklyn, New York and was a SIP Award recipient from the Robert Blackburn [[Printmaking]] Workshop Program at The Elizabeth Foundation for the Arts.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}} Ben-Ari also worked as an [[Artist-in-residence|Artist-in-Residence]] at the [[Lower Manhattan Cultural Council]] Workspace Residency and at the NARS Foundation, New York.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Triangle|title=Artist-In-Residence: Guy Ben-Ari|url=http://www.triangle-arts-association.org/post/137515913991/artist-in-residence-guy-ben-ari|year=2016}}</ref>
