[[File:Yoga-5.png|upright=1.35|thumb|[[Bharatanatyam]], one of the classical sacred dance styles of India]] '''Sacred dance''' is the use of [[dance]] in religious ceremonies and rituals, present in most religions throughout history and prehistory. Its connection with the body and fertility has caused it to be forbidden by some religions; for example, its acceptability in Christianity has varied widely. Dance has formed a major element of worship in Hindu temples with strictly formalized styles such as [[bharatanatyam]], requiring skilled dancers and temple musicians. In the 20th century, sacred dance has been revived by choreographers such as Bernhard Wosien as a means of developing community spirit.<ref name="Gaston Gaston 2014">{{cite book | last=Gaston | first=Anne-Marie (Anjali) | last2=Gaston | first2=Tony | title=Oxford Handbooks Online | chapter=Dance as a Way of Being Religious | publisher=Oxford University Press | date=1 February 2014 | doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780195176674.013.010 | editor=Brown, Frank Burch}}</ref>
==Purposes==
[[W. O. E. Oesterley]] proposed in 1923 that sacred dance had several purposes, the most important being to honour the supernatural powers; the other purposes were to "show off" before the powers; to unite the dancer with the supernatural power (such as with the [[ancient Greece|Greek]]<ref name="Lawler 1947">{{cite journal |last1=Lawler |first1=Lillian Brady |title=The Dance in Ancient Greece |journal=The Classical Journal |date=March 1947 |volume=42 |issue=6 |pages=343–349 |jstor=291645}}</ref> goddesses [[Demeter]] and [[Persephone]]); making the body suitable as a temporary dwelling-place for the deity, by dancing to unconsciousness in [[ecstatic dance]]; making crops grow, or helping or encouraging the deity to make them grow (as with "Ariadne's Dance"); consecrating a victim for sacrifice (as with the [[Israelites]] circling the altar, or the [[Sarawak]] Kayans circling a sacrificial pig); paying homage to the deity present for an initiation ceremony; helping warriors to victory in battle, and appeasing the spirits of the enemy killed in battle; averting the dangers associated with marriage, at a wedding ceremony; and at a funeral or mourning ceremony, purposes such as driving away the malevolent ghost of the dead person, or preventing the ghost from leaving the grave, or frightening off any evil spirits attracted by the corpse, or temporarily and invisibly bringing the dead person back to join in the dance, or simply honouring the dead person.{{sfn|Oesterley|2010|pp=22–30 and passim<!--He structures rest of book around this set of purposes.-->}}
Harriet Lihs in 2009 divided religious [[dance]] into dances of imitation, such as of animals thought to be [[Spirit guide|spirit messenger]]s, or of battles; "medicine dances", i.e. dances of healing, like the serpent dances in India used to prevent disease; commemorative dances, for events such as the [[winter solstice]]; and dances for spiritual connection, as in the whirling dance of the [[Whirling Dervish]]es withn Sufism.{{sfn|Lihs|2009|pp=6–7}}
Laura Shannon in 2018 stated the purposes of contemporary sacred dance as practised at the [[Findhorn Foundation]] as "to be inclusive, mutually supportive, to connect with the earth, spirit and each other, and to become more whole." It was a means of channelling "healing energy" both for the dancers and for their families and communities, indeed for the whole world.<ref name="Shannon 2018"/>
Within religion, [[ecstatic dance]] is one of the ways in which [[religious ecstasy]] is produced.<ref name="Ulland 2012">{{cite journal | last=Ulland | first=Dagfinn | title=Embodied Spirituality | journal=Archive for the Psychology of Religion | volume=34 | issue=1 | date=1 January 2012 | doi=10.1163/157361212x645340 | pages=83–104}}</ref>
==In ancient times== {{further|Ceremonial dance}}
Indigenous [[ceremonial dance]] rituals around the world appear to preserve forms that were widespread in ancient times. For example, processionals and circle dances seen in indigenous dance today were [[Dance in ancient Egypt|used in ancient Egypt]] and among the Hebrews.{{sfn|Lihs|2009|pp=7–8}} In ancient Egypt, dancers impersonated a deity such as the goddess [[Hathor]], taking on the deity's attributes and interpreting the divine world for those watching.<ref name="Mark 2017">{{cite web |last1=Mark |first1=Joshua J. |title=Music & Dance in Ancient Egypt |url=https://www.ancient.eu/article/1075/music--dance-in-ancient-egypt/ |publisher=Ancient History Encyclopedia |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref>
In ancient Israel, [[King David]] danced "before the Lord".<ref>2 [[Samuel (bible)|Samuel]] 6:5</ref><ref name="Mark 2017"/> It is mentioned as something familiar, implying it was a common practice.{{sfn|Oesterley|2010|p=37}} Sacred dance is described in the Bible by verbs meaning dancing, rotating, jumping, skipping, and whirling.{{sfn|Oesterley|2010|pp=44–53}} The dance was accompanied by hand-drums (tambourines), cymbals, flutes, pipes, lyres, harps, and lutes.{{sfn|Oesterley|2010|pp=52}}
The [[Hittites]] are shown in a sacred processional dance in a c. 1200 BC rock inscription at the sanctuary of [[Yazılıkaya]], near their city of [[Hattusa]], in [[Cappadocia]]. A group of men wearing conical hats and tip-tilted shoes, and a group of women, dance in a running step towards a group of named gods and goddesses.{{sfn|Oesterley|2010|p=59}}
In ancient Greece, sacred dance was widespread; indeed, it formed a part of almost all worship, and the gods [[Apollo]], [[Ares]], [[Dionysus]] and [[Pan (god)|Pan]] are all described as dancers, while other deities such as [[Artemis]] were described as dancing with their companions.{{sfn|Oesterley|2010|pp=64, 68}}
The Hawaiian [[Hula]] dances to [[Pele (deity)|Pele]], the volcano goddess, survive, whereas European [[maypole dance]]s have lost their meaning as tree-worship and survive only as folk tradition.{{sfn|Lihs|2009|pp=7–8}}
Lewis Farnell observed that sacred dance has an "extraordinary uniformity" among indigenous peoples all over the world, something that he found so striking that it suggested either "belief in an ultimately identical tradition, or, perhaps more reasonably, the psychologic theory that ... [humans] at the same stage of development respond with the same ... religious act to the same stimuli" from the environment.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Farnell |first1=Lewis Richard |authorlink1=Lewis Richard Farnell |title=The Evolution of Religion {{!}} An Anthropological Study |date=2009 |origyear=2005 |publisher=Cornell University Library |isbn=978-1112156984 |page=2}}</ref> Oesterley suggested that these stimuli to sacred dance were people's response to supernatural power, and "the obtaining of food."{{sfn|Oesterley|2010|pp=2–3}}
<gallery mode=nolines widths=175px heights=175px> File:Hattusa, capital of the Hittite Empire 40.jpg|[[Hittites|Hittite]] gods in a processional dance, [[Yazılıkaya]], [[Hattusa]]. 13th century BC File:Tomb of the Dancers (detail).JPG|thumb|Dancers in ancient Egypt. [[Tomb of the Dancers]], 17th Dynasty, [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]]. 5th or 4th century BC File:Hula Kahiko Hawaii Volcanoes National Park 01.jpg|thumb|[[Hula]] dance in Hawaii derives from the worship of the volcano goddess [[Pele (deity)|Pele]]. File:Ménade relieve romano (Museo del Prado) 04.jpg|Dancing [[maenad]] holding a [[thyrsus]]. Roman copy of 5th century BC Greek original </gallery>
==In world religions== [[File:Whriling dervishes, Rumi Fest 2007.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|[[Whirling Dervishes]]]]
===Christianity===
Some Christian traditions make use of [[Liturgical dance|liturgical]] or [[worship dance]], but it has long been controversial within the church.<ref name="Mark 2017"/> It has been supported, sometimes fervently, by both priests and Christian scholars; and opposed, sometimes stridently, by others who for example wrote some 157 tracts against dance between 1685 and 1963. The early church was largely in favour of dance, as in the 2nd Century ''[[Acts of John]]'' which states that "Grace danceth. I would pipe: dance ye all. The whole world on high hath part in our dancing."{{sfn|Lihs|2009|pp=14–16}} [[Circle dance]] is used, in its more meditative form, in worship within religious traditions including the [[Church of England]].<ref>"We ended with a circle dance." "A short session of circle dance was one of the activities on offer..."{{cite web |url=http://www.st-james-piccadilly.org/sermons/SJPAnnualRpt2006-2007.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214192607/http://www.st-james-piccadilly.org/sermons/SJPAnnualRpt2006-2007.pdf |archivedate=2012-02-14}}</ref><ref>"...we were able to testify our love to the lord using circle dance and hymn singing."[http://www.new-church-lifeline.org.uk/archive/year2001/may2001.pdf]</ref><ref name="Shiloah 2001">{{cite book |last=Shiloah |first=Amnon |title=Music in the World of Islam: A Socio-Cultural Study |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6gwlvp61s4C&pg=PA143 |year=2001 |publisher=Wayne State University Press |isbn=0-8143-2970-5 |page=143}}</ref>
In northern Greece and southern Bulgaria, in the annual celebrations for [[Constantine the Great|Saint Constantine]] and [[Helena (Empress)|Saint Helen]], dancers perform the [[Anastenaria]], a [[fire-walking]] ritual, as the climax of three days of processions, music, dancing, and animal sacrifice.<ref>{{cite book |author=Xygalatas, Dimitris |title=Firewalking and the Brain: The Physiology of High-Arousal Rituals |editor=Joseph Bulbulia, Richard Sosis, Erica Harris, Russell Genet, Cheryl Genet, and Karen Wyman |work=Evolution of Religion: Studies, Theories, and Critiques |publisher=Collins Foundation Press |date=2007 |pages=189-195 |url=http://www.academia.edu/577136/Fire-walking_and_the_Brain_The_Physiology_of_High-Arousal_Rituals}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Xygalatas, Dimitris |date=2011 |title=Ethnography, Historiography, and the Making of History in the Tradition of the Anastenaria |journal=History and Anthropology |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=57-74 |doi=10.1080/02757206.2011.546855}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Danforth, Loring M. |title=Firewalking and Religious Healing: The Anastenaria of Greece and the American Firewalking Movement |publisher=Princeton University Press |date=1989 |isbn=978-0691028538}}</ref>
===Hinduism=== {{further|Indian classical dance|Nataraja}}
[[Indian classical dance]]s such as [[Bharatanatyam]], [[Kathak]], [[Odissi]], and [[Mohiniattam]] can be traced to the Sanskrit text ''[[Natya Shastra]]''.<ref name=lochtefeld467>{{cite book |author=Lochtefeld, James G. |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism: N-Z |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g6FsB3psOTIC&pg=PA467 |year=2002 |publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-8239-3180-4 |pages=467 |quote=the Natyashastra remains the ultimate authority for any dance form that claims to be 'classical' dance, rather than 'folk' dance.}}</ref><ref name=khokar57>{{cite book |author=Khokar, Mohan |title=Traditions of Indian classical dance |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=prjnAAAAMAAJ |year=1984 |publisher=Clarion Books |pages=57–58}}</ref> They are a traditional drama-dance expression of religion,<ref name="Brown2013p195">{{cite book |editor=Brown, Frank Burch |title=The Oxford Handbook of Religion and the Arts |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X8g8BAAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-972103-0 |pages=195–196 |quote=All of the dances considered to be part of the Indian classical canon (Bharata Natyam, Chhau, Kathak, Kathakali, Manipuri, Mohiniattam, Odissi, Sattriya and Yakshagana) trace their roots to religious practices (...) the Indian diaspora has led to the translocation of Hindu dances to Europe, North America and the world.}}</ref> related to [[Vaishnavism]], [[Shaivism]], [[Shaktism]], pan-Hindu Epics and the Vedic literature.<ref>{{cite book |author=Devi, Ragini |title=Dance Dialects of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KRz5ykKRVAEC |year=1990 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0674-0 |pages=25-30, 67-68, 166}}</ref> As a religious art, they are either performed inside the [[Sanctum (Temple)|sanctum]] of a Hindu temple, or near it.<ref name=lipner206>{{cite book |author=Lipner, Julius |authorlink=Julius J. Lipner |title=Hindus: Their Religious Beliefs and Practices |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qv3fCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA206 |year=2012 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-24061-5 |page=206 |quote=Hindu classical dance... developed in a religious context and was given high profile as part of temple worship. There are a number of regional and other styles as well as source texts, but the point we wish to stress is the participative nature of such dance. In form and content, the heart of dance as worship in Hinduism has always been 'expression' (abhinaya), i.e. the enacting of various themes.}}</ref><ref name=holmbowker85>{{cite book |author1=Holm, Jean |author2=Bowker, John |title=Worship |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s_nUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA85 |year=1994 |publisher=Bloomsbury |isbn=978-1-85567-111-9 |page=85 |quote=Hindu classical dance-forms, like Hindu music, are associated with worship. References to dance and music are found in the vedic literature...}}</ref>
===Islam and Sufism===
Dance is unusual within Islam, but circle dance is used in the Islamic [[Haḍra]] dances.<ref name="Shiloah 2001"/> In the tradition of the [[Mevlevi Order]] founded by [[Rumi]], ecstatic<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Erzen |first1=Jale |title=The Dervishes Dance -- The Sacred Ritual of Love |url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/spo.7523862.0006.007 |journal=Contemporary Aesthetics |volume=6 |date=2008}}</ref> [[Sufi whirling]] is practised by devotees as a form of active meditation within the [[Sema|Sama]] (worship ceremony).<ref name="MOA sema">{{cite web |url=http://www.hayatidede.org/popups/about_sema.htm |title=The Sema of the Mevlevi |publisher=Mevlevi Order of America |accessdate=2009-03-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121221021339/http://www.hayatidede.org/popups/about_sema.htm |archivedate=21 December 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2007, Sufi practices including ecstatic dance and the reciting of religious poetry were a focus for political resistance in Iran, reportedly "demoniz[ed]" by [[Shi'a]] clerics.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scolieri |first1=Paul |title=Introduction Global/Mobile: Re-orienting Dance and Migration Studies |journal=Dance Research Journal |date=2008 |volume=40 |issue=2 (Winter) |page=XVII}}</ref>
===Syncretic===
The syncretic [[Afro-American religion|Afro-American religious tradition]] [[Candomblé]], practiced mainly in [[Brazil]], makes use of music and ecstatic dance in which worshippers become possessed by their own tutelary deities, [[Orisha]]s.<ref name="BBC">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/candomble/ataglance/glance.shtml "Religions - Candomblé: Candomblé at glance"]. [[BBC]]. 15 September 2009. Retrieved 7 January 2014.</ref>
[[File:Ruth St Denis in Egypta 1910 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|[[Ruth St. Denis]], in a dance pose inspired by the Egyptian goddess [[Isis]]. Photographed by [[Otto Sarony]], 1910.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bernstein |first1=Matthew |last2=Studlar |first2=Gaylyn |title=Visions of the East: Orientalism in Film |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q2_E_gl9BbYC&pg=PA134 |year=1997 |publisher=I.B.Tauris |isbn=978-1-86064-305-7 |page=134}}</ref>]]
==Modern==
Choreographers starting with [[Isadora Duncan]], [[Ruth St. Denis]] and her husband [[Ted Shawn]], and [[Martha Graham]] developed [[contemporary dance]] early in the 20th century, often using elements of sacred dance and fusing them with other genres. Later choreographers also made use of themes from the bible.<ref name=SDG>{{cite web |title=About Sacred Dance |url=http://sacreddanceguild.org/about/about-sacred-dance/ |publisher=Sacred Dance Guild |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref name="Clemente 2008">{{cite journal | last=Clemente | first=Karen | title=The Sacred or the Profane: The Challenge of Modern Dance in Religious Educational Settings | journal=Journal of Dance Education | volume=8 | issue=2 | year=2008 | doi=10.1080/15290824.2008.10387360 | pages=62–72}}</ref>
The [[Mysticism|mystic]] and spiritual teacher [[George Gurdjieff]] collected or authored a series of sacred dances, known as [[Gurdjieff movements]], and taught them to his students as part of what he considered the work of ''self observation'' and ''self study''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction |url=http://gurdjieff-dances.com/eng/ |publisher=Gurdjieff Dances |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>
The [[Dances of Universal Peace]], created by North American Sufis, use dancing, Sufi whirling, and singing of sacred phrases from different religions to raise consciousness and promote peace between diverse religions.<ref>{{cite web |title=About The Dances of Universal Peace |url=https://www.dancesofuniversalpeace.org/about.shtm |publisher=Dances of Universal Peace |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>{{sfn|Lihs|2009|p=17}}
From 1976, the ballet master and choreographer {{ill|Bernhard Wosien|de}} introduced [[circle dance]] at the [[Findhorn Foundation]] in Scotland. He used both traditional dances and his own choreography to develop "group awareness".{{sfn|Watts|2006|pp=6–10}} Wosien's approach was taken up by Anna Barton, both at Findhorn and across Europe in the 1980s, and this style of sacred dance spread around the world.<ref name="Shannon 2018">{{cite web |last1=Shannon |first1=Laura |title=Sacred Dance, Armenian Dance |url=https://www.findhorn.org/blog/sacred-dance-in-findhorn/ |publisher=[[Findhorn Foundation]] |accessdate=3 November 2018 |date=30 May 2018}}</ref>{{-}}
